% Link the argument with the methods I will use: Granger Causality Test
\paragraph{Granger-causality Tests}

% explain argument, break and what granger is
The emergence of a new industrial sector rose a new politically disenfranchised elite who demanded political and economic reforms, ending years of political asymmetries. In exchange for these demands, the industrial sector accepted to be income-taxed, setting countries in a path of both political and long-run economic development. The income tax, as an institution that contributed to develop further state capacities and institutional development, should then be associated with long-term economic growth, and consequently with a secular relative decline of agriculture and substantial relative expansion of manufacturing. To confirm this hypothesis, the theory should pass a number of tests. First, \emph{before} the inter-sectoral compromises (i.e., before the income tax law was implemented), political institutions and social norms inherited from the colonial period were designed to allocate economic inputs (and hence \emph{growth}) in a way that benefited the landowning class only. Hence, I expect the transference of economic inputs to go \emph{from} the industrial sector \emph{to} the agriculture sector, a \emph{backwards} equilibrium as stated by the dual sector model. Second, \emph{after} the income tax was implemented, we should see a \emph{reversion} of the flow of inputs, generating growth \emph{from} the agricultural sector \emph{to} the industrial sector. In econometric terms, we should see that the income tax reverted the way in which one sector `Granger-caused' the other.\footnote{This is not an experimental design, and hence the term `causation' should be taken loosely. As \citet[241]{Beck1992} explains, cointegration is not causal.} \citet[42]{Lutkepohl2006} explains that if some variable $X$ forecasts variable $Y$ (and not vise versa), $X$ is said to `Granger-cause' $Y$. According to \citet[349]{Granger1980}, this concept of `causation' is based on the idea ``that the future cannot cause the past.''\footnote{See \citet[197]{Durr1992} for a similar definition.}


