% comment Granger Tests
In \autoref{granger:table} I test for Granger-causation, i.e. the directionality in which economic growth was produced both prior and after the implementation of the income tax law.\footnote{Specifically, the tests were computed after estimating the reduced form VAR specified in \autoref{var:1}.} The table strongly suggests that the income tax caused a structural transformation in (almost) all `developed' countries, namely Chile, Colombia and Mexico. In all these cases the income tax reverted the initial inter-sectoral growth equilibrium suggesting a contested elite structure, as the case of Chile conveys. Before the income tax law, industrial development Granger-caused agricultural development, and after the income tax law, the agricultural sector Granger-caused industrial development (all p-values are significant at the $.05$ level).\footnote{Except for the Mexico after the implementation of the income tax (p-value = $.06$).} These results suggest that the implementation of the income tax was associated to the overthrowing of the political institutions and practices that permitted agricultural expansion at the expenses of the modern sector, and that the reversion of the original backwards macroeconomic structure set in motion a path of long-term economic development.\footnote{See specially next \hyperref[var:theory]{section}.} In Nicaragua and Guatemala the tests suggest the exact opposite (all p-values are significant at the $.05$ level).\footnote{Except for the pre income tax period test of Guatemala, which is significant at the $.1$ level.} The implementation of the income tax in these countries did \emph{not} revert the initial backward macroeconomic equilibrium because when lately implemented, the tax did not reflect the inter-sectoral tensions, challenges and compromises proper of the contested political economies. The industrial sector never had enough economic leverage to politically confront the landowning elite (see \autoref{sectoral:outputs:fig:1}) and hence industrialists never posed credible threats to the status quo, relaxing the endogenous incentives to invest in state institutions. The Argentinian case is different. In line with the historical references, the Granger tests are inconclusive, and no significant results were found, suggesting a weak inter-sectoral cleavage structure.




